@node "AddMIME" "Included scripts/AddMIME.thor"
@TOC Scripts

@{b}AddMIME.thor@{ub}

   Attach  a  file  (MIME) while writing a msg in Thor.  Run from FSE,
CED or GED.  Borrowed some code from InsertIt.thor (by Shaun Downend).

@endnode

@node "AddUser" "Included scripts/AddUser.thor"
@TOC Scripts

@{b}AddUser.thor@{ub}

    This  script  will let you add the sender or any of the recipients
of  the  current message to the user database in THOR.  Name, address,
alias and a comment can be entered or altered.

@endnode

@node "BuildList" "Included scripts/BuildList.thor"
@TOC Scripts

@{b}BuildList.thor@{ub}

   This  script  will  let you build a file containing a list of BBSes
and  conferences  for use with @{"MultiUpload.thor" Link MultiUpload}.
First  choose or enter the name of the file you want to hold the list.
Then  pick  BBS  names  and  conference  names until you are finished.
Pressing  escape or clicking on the closegadget in the conference list
window  will  leave the conference field empty, useful for MultiUpload
lists where you don't want to make the upload private to a conference.

@endnode

@node "BulkMail" "Included scripts/BulkMail.thor"
@TOC Scripts

@{b}BulkMail.thor@{ub}

                         BulkMail.thor  V2.0

                        © Neil Bothwick, 1997

BullkMail was originally written to send copies of a mail message to
multiple recipients. since i had a need to send these out as
individual mails, including multiple recipients on the To: line or
using cc: were not suitable.

Several people have asked for enhancements, so here is version 2.

Features of BulkMail 2.0
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

*  Searches on either comment or alias field of user database for
   matching addresses

*  Send a separate mail to each recipient, or a single mail with
   the other recipients on a Cc: or Bcc: header

*  Search the user database using a string based on the address of
   the original message, or from a user-defined hotlist

*  Either use all matching address, or select from a list.


Using BulkMail 2.0
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

1)  Create the mail message you wish to send

2)  Select this message in the Events Editor and run BulkMail

3)  Enter a search string, you can either type it in, use the from
    address or select a string from your own hotlist. The hotlist is
    useful if you regularly send mails to groups of people. You need
    to create the hotlist yourself, it is called BulkMail.hotlist and
    needs to be in the data directory for the current system (e.g. BBS0)

4)  Select to search on either Alias or comment

5)  You will be shown the number of matches and be given the choice of
    using all of them, or selecting from the list

6)  Choose either to send separate mails to each recipient, or to add
    them to the current mail as Cc: or Bcc: headers. The difference
    between the last two is that the the Cc: (carbon copy) header will
    appear in all copies of the mail received, whereas Bcc: (blind
    carbon copy) won't

7)  If you chose separate messages, you will be given the option of
    deleting the original message.


Bug reports
~~~~~~~~~~~

I have tested BulkMail here, but would appreciate reports on any bugs
you may find. I would also like to here from anyone who uses it
without any problems, just so I know it's working OK.


Neil Bothwick
neil\@wirenet.u-net.com

@endnode

@node "CalcDl" "Included scripts/CalcDl.thor"
@TOC Scripts

@{b}CalcDl.thor@{ub}

   This  script  will  calculate  an  estimate  of  the time needed to
download  files  selected  in  Thor  and  present  the  results  in  a
requester.   In  order to do this the files will have to be present in
Thor's  file  database.  It can be run either in the Startup Window or
from inside a system.

Change  the  cpsrate  variable  in the start of the script to whatever
your modem is capable of.

@endnode

@node "CEDDownload" "Included scripts/CEDDownload.thor"
@TOC Scripts

@{b}CEDDownload.thor@{ub}

   This  script is very simple.  Place the cursor on a filename in CED
(CygnusEditor) and start the script.  THOR will request a BBS name and
a  download event will created with the filename from CED.  Useful for
browsing through a filelist in CED and selecting files to download.

   A  permanent  BBS  name can be specified in the script if you don't
want the BBS name requester to pop up for every filename.

   For  details  on  how  to  make CED execute CEDDownload.thor on the
press of a function key, check out page 94 in your CED v3.5 manual.

   This  script  only  works  for  BBS  systems and can not be used to
create download events for files on Aminet.

@endnode

@node "CleanSystem" "Included scripts/CleanSystem.thor"
@TOC Scripts

@{b}CleanSystem.thor@{ub}

THOR should remove all files relating to a conference when you delete
it, but sometimes it doesn't. The reason i that it waits until all
THOR processes have finished, so if you have ConnectTHOR running but
hidden and reset, or your machine is reset before quitting THOR, you
will be left with some `orphaned' files taking up space in your data
directory.

Run this script from the Arexx menu in THOR and it will removed all
orphaned files in the current system, prompting you for confirmation
first.

@endnode

@node "CopyMessages" "Included scripts/CopyMessages.thor"
@TOC Scripts

@{b}CopyMessages.thor@{ub}

CopyMessages.thor will let you copy messages in similar manner to
what the "Move Messages" menu item in Thor does. The difference is
that CopyMessages does not delete the original messages afterwards
(of course) and that it allows you to copy messages between systems.

To use the script simply run it from the ARexx menu in Thor. The
messages can be multiselected in the "Messages in conference" window,
otherwise the currently displayed message will be copied.

If the destination conference does not exist it can be created if
you select "Create new conference" in the destinaion conference 
selector that pops up. The new conference will get the same
attributes as the original conference. Note that Thor uses a flag
to specify the type of a confererence (EMail, news, folder and
local currently). This version of CopyMessages will not allow you
to specify a type for the new conference, it will inherit the type
from the source conference.

@endnode

@node "DeleteRange" "Included scripts/DeleteRange.thor"
@TOC Scripts

@{b}DeleteRange.thor@{ub}

  Delete a specified range of messages.

@endnode

@node "Event2Msg" "Included scripts/Event2Msg.thor"
@TOC Scripts

@{b}Event2Msg.thor@{ub}

   Moves the current event to any conference (on the same system).

   Handy  if  you're  writing scripts for Thor and you need a msg that
contains  a  sertain text, but you can't find it in your database.  So
now  you can write your own msg (event) and use this script to move it
to  your  desired  conference.   It can also handle one attached file.
After  the  event  is  moved  the  entered  msg  will  be shown in the
destination conference.

HISTORY
1.1 - Now works correcly with systems and conferences that contain spaces.
    - Fixed a problem with the Thor ARexx port.

@endnode

@node "JoinNewGroup" "Included scripts/JoinNewGroup.thor"
@TOC Scripts

@{b}JoinNewGroup.thor@{ub}

Whenever you get news with Thor, it also gets a list of new newsgroups
on your news server and presents these as an article in a conference
called Information, as well as adding them to the main conference list.

Unfortunately you then have to wait for the full list to load into
memory (over 20,000 groups with my provider) before you can join one
of the new ones.

This script presents the newsgroups from the current information
message in a listview, and creates a join event for the one you
select. Assigning it to a function key means you can join new
groups almost instantly.

@endnode

@node "GetNet" "Included scripts/GetNet.thor"
@TOC Scripts

@{b}GetNet.thor@{ub}

GetNET.thor 1.4 (26.6.96) by Remco van Hooff (rvhooff\@globalxs.nl)

GetNET can do 2 things:

1: Grab http adresses (WWW addresses) from the current message, and save
   them to the hotlist of your favourite WWW browser(s).
   Browsers currently supported are:
 
   AMosaic
   AWeb
   IBrowse (0.81+)
   Voyager
   HTML is also supported which can be read by any browser.

2: Grab email addresses from the current message, and save them to the
   userlist of your Internet system.

REQUIREMENTS:
- Thor 2.2+
- COPY and DELETE somewhere in your path
- A WWW browser (Amosaic, IBrowse, ALynx, AWeb, ...),
  only for the www addresses.

USAGE:
As usual you need to edit some variables:

- Edit the BBS variable to point to your Internet system.

- Edit the HOTLIST_* variables for the right path/file for the hotlists.

- Edit the AMOSAIC/IBROWSE/VOYAGER/AWEB/HTML variables:
  1 = save to hitlist, 
  0 = don't save to hotlist
  You can have all set to 1 if you use all the browsers, or 0 if you don't
  want to save anything :.) (you'll be notified if you have turned all off).

- Edit the LOOP variable: 
  0 = loop
  1 = no loop
  This variable will enable you to return to the main requester (chose
  between HTTP, Email or Quit) after you've saved email/http addresses.

- You can also edit the filter chars, I already included the most common
  chars. The '.' is "hardcoded" and is therefore not included in the filter
  list.
  A filter character is a character that may be "connected" to an address,
  e.g. <email\@address.somewhere>
  The '<' and '>' are not part of the actual address and thus should be
  removed.
  So filters for these characters are: filter.1.x = '>', filter.2.x = '<'
  filter.1.x are used for chars that follow the address (http and email)
  filter.2.x are used for chars that preceed the address (email only)

Note: 
- You can leave the name of the address empty, they will automatically be
  replaced by a default name.
  If you selected HTTP the default name is 'subj (i)', subj is
  the subject of the msg without 'Re:'. 
  If you selected Email the default name is the userid (eg rvhooff in
  rvhooff\@globalxs.nl).
- Duplicate addresses will not be shown.
- The HTTP oprion will search the msg HEADER, the Email option will not.
  
AUTHOR:
For bugs, comments, flames, typos, optimizing tips:
Internet: rvhoof\@globalxs.nl
FIDO    : 2:286/407.39
AMY     : 39:153/201.39
Also have a look at my homepage for more Thor ARexx scripts.
http://www.globalxs.nl/home/r/rvhooff

HISTORY:
 1.0 - Joined 2 programs (GetHTTP and GetEmail) together into one program. 
       The programs use a lot of similar code, so joining them together
       will use less HD space :.)

 1.1 - Added AWeb hotlist support.
     - Removed 'GetNet -' from default names when saving to the hotlists.
     - Added loop option. You can now chose if you want to return to the start
       requester or not.
     - Changed the IBrowse hotlist format to that of verion 0.81.

 1.2 - Added Voyager hotlist support.

 1.3 - Fixed some trouble with arexx ports when ConnectThor was running.
 
 1.4 - Addresses that don't start with 'http://' but do start with 'www.'
       will now also be shown.
     - Fixed a bug in the HTML save routine (does anybody use it?).

TO DO:
- More hotlists (send me a short hotlist if you want to have it supported).
- GetFTP. I'm still working on it.
  The code will either search for 'ftp://', for x.x.domain (or #.#.#.#), or
  both. The first option will be as fast as that of GetNET, the latter 2
  will be slow (I'll have to check against 200+ domains) and will therefore
  be implemented as an option.

  The found addresses will be saved to the hotlist of your WWW browser.
  This is the only solution until I can get my hands on the formats of FTP
  clients, so if you are an FTP client author please post me the format of
  the hotlist. If you're not an author but do know what the format of a
  certain client is please post it to me and I'll ask permission from the
  author.

@endnode

